Feb 4 2009 	Great deal for Manhattan!	I had meetings at Pace University, and this was the closest Hilton family property. I was afraid of what I'd find when I booked a rate of $122 for a Sunday night, which is technically a business night. Granted, it was also superbowl evening, so there may have been fewer bookings in general. Anyway, after the typical harrowing ride from LGA, I was pretty pleasantly surprised. The hotel is pretty new, and the front desk guy was nice and helpful. Per the Manhattan norm, everything is small--lobby, front desk, lone elevator, hallways. Surprisingly, however, the room was pretty spacious, and the bathroom was just fine by NYC standards. The room offered normal Hampton bedding (ok, not great), a small desk, decent desk chair, great desk lamp, separate closet, and a flat screen TV mounted on the wall. Nothing fancy, but then again, it's a Hampton Inn. The hotel IS loud (below my window was, it seemed, a bus depot and bulldozer terminal), but the HVAC drowned out the noise well enough to sleep. The free breakfast was typical Hampton--fine, unpretentious--though the eating area was tee-niny. The area is pretty dead at night, but there were at least five restaurants open w/in a two block radius. Stellas was great. Oh, there's a v-e-r-y sparse, small workout room in the basement, but it was good enough for 30 minutes of cardio. All in all, for less than $150 in Manhattan, this is a great option.	
