May 11 2007 	Comfort Service and Location....	I stayed in this hotel for a week on business and found the room large, (by NYC standards), the bed comfortable, the bathroom big and the whole place very clean. The room had a great flat screen TV, a nice size desk, free internet (but bring your own laptop) and free breakfast. The breakfast was not elaborate, but it was adequate including fruit, yogurt, cereals, breads, muffins, bagels, and 2 hot selections that varied each day. The location is only 2 blocks from the South St Seaport, so there are several nice restaurants nearby. I loved Acqua and the Dodo Cafe. In addition, the hotel is within 3 blocks of 2 of the major subway lines, so you can quickly be uptown, or anywhere else you need to go. I was particularly impressed with the service since I had to leave on very short notice and had put in dry cleaning for next day return. The helpful staff got it back from the dry cleaners for me within hours so I could leave town with all my clothes ! Also, when I returned to the hotel each day after work, they had warm complimentary cookies for the guests-a nice touch.Just one piece of advice, my room was on the ground floor and although I did not mind because I wear earplugs when I sleep, the ground floor rooms are noisy because you get lobby noise.	
May 9 2007 	Really liked this hotel highly recommend it	Spent three night at this hotel and would highly recommend it. The location is great: right next to the Brooklyne bridge and the South street Seaport area for shops and attractions. Battery park and city hall are a short walk away and there are several subway stations in the area. The hotel is small, I was told they opened recently, so it is overall pretty new, clean and very well kept. It was family friendly, we were there with a 4 year old and he loved it. The staff at the front desk was extremely helpful and courteous. When we got to the hotel they gave me a tour of the various rooms available so I could choose then one I liked the most. We had a room with two queen beds, it was fairly large by NYC standards. Had a desk, a window facing Pearl St, flat screen tv, two telephones, coffee maker etc. The beds and bed linens were new, very clean, very comfortable, you get plenty of pillows to choose the one you like best. The bed was definitely a plus to me! The batroom was large, very clean, with bathtub, hairdryer, plenty of supplies. Overall the room was nice, well decorated, modern, and very clean. We were on the 4th floor, facing the street, and it was only slightly noisy. It wasn't a problem for us, but if you have trouble falling asleep maybe ask for a room in the back, not one facing Pearl St.Another thing I liked a lot is that breakfast is included, and offered several nice options: fruit, yogurt, cereal, muffins, bread, butter, jam, eggs, sausages and plenty of juices, coffee, tea. It was nice to wake up and be able to have breakfast at the hotel, and head out ready to savour NYC. One last tip, one block from the hotel there is an Italian restaurant called Acqua. The hotel staff recommended it and I was a bit suspicious, but I was wrong. It was so good that we went there twice, and I'm 100% Italian, so you can trust my judgment on this one! We had home made pasta both nights, they had gnocchi, pappardelle, a great wine list, and fantastic desserts (we tried the pistacchio and mascarpone gelato, and it was really good!). For $188 a night (we were there over the w/e) + taxes I don't think I could have found better value for money in NYC!	
Apr 26 2007 	Service with a Smile--MINE!	I just spent one night at the Hamptom Inn--what a pleasant surprise! Fantastic service--front desk, maids, even the guy powerwashing the sidewalk outside the hotel! EX: I checked in 5 hours earlier than the check-in time, and was treated like royalty. No hassle, no issues. At first they thought they wouldn't have a room available--and they recommended I did not accept the 1st floor room that they believed was available b/c of the street noise--but quickly found an available room on a higher floor.Rooms with great design features and amenities--clean, funky, comfortable, great bed and linens, flat screen wall-mounted tv. (While the rooms are small, even by NY standards, the service and surroundings well make up for it!)For a really small hotel, it was such an overwhelming treat to experience a stay at the Hampton Inn.	
Apr 24 2007 	What a Great Deal!	This is a great little hotel with friendly staff, clean comfy rooms and a great location. I booked the room for my first visit to NYC. A friend came with me, who has been to NYC several times. She was impressed with the hotel and room and said she would definitely stay here again. Same with me, I have at least one more trip to NYC planned and I will stay here. I'm very picky about cleanliness in a hotel room, (I travel for business a lot). This hotel passed my high standards. The bathroom was very clean, The beds were comfy and the sheets and bedding were of good decent quality. They serve free breakfast in the morning, nothing fancy, scrambled eggs, sausage, sometimes fresh waffles, breads, fruits, yogurts, cereals, juices and coffees, but it more than satisfies. Although, I didn't use it, they have free internet in the rooms.I almost hesitate to write this review, while the hotel deserves a great review, I want to keep this a secret all to myself and a few good friends!	
Apr 2 2007 	Hamptons Shining Star - Don't Stay Anywhere Else	My wife and I have been visiting New York for several years and we were already aware of Hampton Inns great value for money, however our first visit to their Seaport location was the best thing we have ever done. This hotel is shining star in the Hampton galaxy, the rooms are spotlessly clean with huge beds and soft marshmallow bedding that you just sink into, there's plasma TV in every room, ice and soda machines on most landings and a compact gym in the basement. We are talking 4 to 5 star quality without the over dressing.Included in the terrific rates is a complimentary hot and cold buffet breakfast with as much as you can eat. There's no bar or restaurant but that doesn't matter as right around the corner is a great diner and a host of fabulous Seafood, Italian, Steak, Japanese and traditional restaurants. Seaport is like a step back in time with cobbled streets and old warehouses that are now modern shops and bars etc. It's an Oasis in the heart of New York. The Hampton Seaport is right under the Brooklyn Bridge, just a block from the subway (10 mins to Empire State) and 5 minute stroll to Ground Zero.The staff were terriic, very helpful and friendly. One of the greatest surprises when we finally climbed into bed was the silence, no sirens, car horns, people shouting just warm comfortable sweet dreams. Can't wait to go back.	
